It is important that todays websites conform to both good design and good web content 
accessibility principles.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="3" relname="span">  Tim Berners-Lee states that The power of the Web is in its 
universality. Access by everyone regardless of disability is an essential aspect&quot; (W3C, 
2004).</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="2" relname="elaboration">  It is important that designers develop websites that is accessible by all users, 
through any type of system, and under any constraints (W3C, 1999).</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="3" relname="background"> The Web Accessible 
Initiative (WAI), under guidance of the W3C organization has developed guidelines and 
considerations for developing website.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="10" relname="span">

Designers must always target all users and not just a majority.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="means">  Following good principles 
and guidelines does not restrict development, as what some designers believe, but 
promote good design practices.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="11" relname="summary">  These principles enable all users to use sites without 
difficulty or frustration.</segment>
